natural problem: In triangle $ABC,$ $\sin A = \frac{3}{5}$ and $\sin B = \frac{24}{25}.$  Enter all the possible values of $\sin C,$ separated by commas.
natural solution: We have that \[\cos^2 A = 1 - \sin^2 A = \frac{16}{25},\]so $\cos A = \pm \frac{4}{5}.$

Similarly, \[\cos^2 B = 1 - \sin^2 B = \frac{49}{625},\]so $\cos B = \pm \frac{7}{25}.$ Then \begin{align} \sin C &= \sin (180^\circ - A - B) \\ &= \sin (A + B) \\ &= \sin A \cos B + \cos A \sin B \\ &= \frac{3}{5} \left( \pm \frac{7}{25} \right) + \left( \pm \frac{4}{5} \right) \frac{24}{25}.

\end{align}The possible values of this expression are $\pm \frac{3}{5}$ and $\pm \frac{117}{125}.$  But $\sin C$ must be positive, so the possible values of $\sin C$ are $\boxed{\frac{3}{5}, \frac{117}{125}}.$
